{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-help-when-to-call-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What a ProAdvisor is for &mdash; and what they&rsquo;re not.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor is an accounting professional certified by Intuit to set up, repair, and run QuickBooks &mdash; the operational work that lives <em>inside your books</em>. You call one when the numbers themselves need help: the file is behind or messy, reconciliation won&rsquo;t tie, you need a cleanup ahead of a deadline, you&rsquo;re standing up or moving a QuickBooks file, or you simply need books you can trust. The deciding question is always &ldquo;is the problem in the <em>accounting</em>?&rdquo; &mdash; if so, it&rsquo;s a ProAdvisor call.</p>
      <p>What a ProAdvisor is <em>not</em> is Intuit. An independent firm can&rsquo;t reach into your Intuit account, reset your login, change your subscription or billing, or patch a software bug &mdash; those are Intuit&rsquo;s to handle, and trying to route them to us only slows you down. The honest split below keeps the two apart: the situations that genuinely warrant a ProAdvisor, the loudest call-now signals, and exactly what to do first &mdash; including when the right move is to call Intuit instead.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

